      <solution>
        <p>We follow <xref ref="def_surfacearea">Definition</xref>. We start by noting that <m>f_x(x,y) = -1</m> and <m>f_y(x,y) = -2</m>. To define <m>R</m>, we use bounds <m>0\leq y\leq 2-x/2</m> and <m>0\leq x\leq 4</m>. Therefore
          <md>
            <mrow>S \amp = \iint_R\ dS</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \int_0^4\int_0^{2-x/2} \sqrt{1+(-1)^2+(-2)^2}\ dy\ dx</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \int_0^4 \sqrt{6}\left(2-\frac x2\right)\ dx</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = 4\sqrt{6}.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>Because the surface is a triangle, we can figure out the area using geometry. Considering the base of the triangle to be the side in the <m>x</m>-<m>y</m> plane, we find the length of the base to be <m>\sqrt{20}</m>. We can find the height using our knowledge of vectors: let <m>\vec u</m> be the side in the <m>x</m>-<m>z</m> plane and let <m>\vec v</m> be the side in the <m>x</m>-<m>y</m> plane. The height is then <m>\norm {\vec u - \proj{u}{v}} = 4\sqrt{6/5}</m>. Geometry states that the area is thus
          <me>
            \frac 12\cdot4\sqrt{6/5}\cdot\sqrt{20} = 4\sqrt{6}.
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>We affirm the validity of our formula.</p>
      </solution>
